      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for your query:\n\n## \"Position: The No Free Lunch Theorem, Kolmogorov Complexity, and the Role of Inductive Biases in Machine Learning\"\n\nThis is a position paper presented at **ICML 2024** as a **Spotlight** paper.\n\n**Authors:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Micah Goldblum, Marc Finzi, Keefer Rowan, and Andrew Gordon Wilson"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ".\n\n**Publication:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Proceedings of the 41st International Conference on Machine Learning, PMLR 235:15788-15808, 2024."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "No free lunch theorems for supervised learning state that no learner can solve all problems or that all learners achieve exactly the same accuracy on average over a uniform distribution on learning problems. Accordingly, these theorems are often referenced in support of the notion that individual problems require specially tailored inductive biases."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nThe authors challenge this interpretation: "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "While virtually all uniformly sampled datasets have high complexity, real-world problems disproportionately generate low-complexity data, and they argue that neural network models share this same preference, formalized using Kolmogorov complexity."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nKey findings include:\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They show that architectures designed for a particular domain, such as computer vision, can compress datasets on a variety of seemingly unrelated domains."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Their experiments show that pre-trained and even randomly initialized language models prefer to generate low-complexity sequences."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Whereas no free lunch theorems seemingly indicate that individual problems require specialized learners, they explain how tasks that often require human intervention such as picking an appropriately sized model can be automated into a single learning algorithm. These observations justify the trend in deep learning of unifying seemingly disparate problems with an increasingly small set of machine learning models."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Key Links\n\n- **ICML proceedings:** https://proceedings.mlr.press/v235/goldblum24a.html\n- **arXiv:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.05366\n- **OpenReview:** https://openreview.net/forum?id=EaJ7nqJ2Fa"
      }
    ],
